div.p:
               Mademoielle de la Fleur who cou'd not well diget the box o'th' Ear, did not return one Word, but pretending that he wou'd go up into her Chamber, he privately pack'd up all her Goods and Chattels, and pas'd immediately thro' the Garden;


from whence he got out at a Backdoor, which open'd directly into the ame Street where the Marhal lodg'd, who aw her come forth as he was looking out of the Window. He was never more urpris'd in his Life time, than when he perceiv'd her Eyes all Red and Swell'd with Tears. What can be the matter Mademoielle, aid he, coming towards her; dare I be o bold as to ask you, what makes you weep thus? Alas! Sir Said he, I am undone. The Marhal, who was jut by his Lodgings, made her a ign to follow him, not thinking it a proper place there, to talk of matters of Moment. It is not very Convenient, reply'd he with a bluh, to go with you into your Lodgings, but what matter is it, I am deperate and care not what becomes of me? That is all but a Jet, anwer'd the Marhal, taking her by the Hand, I will tell my Land-Lady you are my Siter, which he did, and the good Woman believ'd it for a coniderable time. Our fair one being gone up with the Marhal into his Chamber, burt out all in Tears, giving him an account of what had pas'd between the Lady and her: To give a box on the Ear to a Gentlewoman of my Quality, aid he, and that too, for no other reaon but becaue I had dicours'd with a Gentleman of Honour, certainly is the mot unbecoming Action that ever cou'd be


done by a enible Woman. I am quite out of all Patience, reply'd Boufflers, if I were to follow my Inclination, I hou'd go and tick that old Witch, who inform'd her of it to the Wall; he often paes by here, and I'll have her Batonado'd by one of my Servants, he hall have the Strapado till the Blood follows. Have a care of that, reply'd Janneton, for that wou'd be the way to undo me without Redres. And what my Dearet, aid the Marhal embracing her, wou'd you not have me revenge your Quarrel, I aure you that I hall always be ready to hazard my Life for your ake. 'Tis I who am the caue of thee extravagancies which my Couin has committed againt you, and I ask your Pardon a thouand times upon that account.
